Nothing prevents the streams client backlog from growing to the point that they exceed the system's client capacity. This has to do with the implementation of com.atlassian.util.concurrent.LimitedExecutor to which it eventually delegates its completion service management. This has an internal "overflow" queue that is allowed to grow without bounds. If the LinkedBlockingQueue was given a bounds, then trying to queue up too many clients would throw an IllegalStateException, which could be caught and mapped to a busy message. "Unable to load the activity stream at this time. This system is too busy." or something like that. It's ugly,but better than allowing so many clients to queue up that no http threads are available to process anything else.

